<Layout title="Research | Riccardo Fracchioni">

<h1>Research</h1>

<p>
My research lies at the intersection of philosophy of artificial
intelligence, philosophy of science, and epistemology.
</p>


<h2>
AI-based scientific methods and explanatory understanding
</h2>

<p>
I investigate how machine learning models reshape scientific
methodology and the epistemic practices involved in scientific
discovery. A central question of my research is whether AI systems
can contribute to scientific understanding despite often lacking
traditional forms of mechanistic explanation.
</p>


<h2>
Large Language Models and semantic competence
</h2>

<p>
My previous research focused on the assessment of semantic competence
in Large Language Models. I explored the relationship between
distributional representations, formal semantics, and theories of
meaning, asking whether computational models can acquire genuinely
semantic abilities.
</p>


<h2>
Machine learning and scientific explanation
</h2>

<p>
I am interested in the epistemological role of machine learning
models in science, including questions concerning prediction,
interpretability, causality, and the relationship between statistical
patterns and theoretical understanding.
</p>


</Layout>